answers.body_markdown:
You are on the right track.  
You first need to split the [polynomial] string into terms where the terms are delimited by the plus sign, i.e. `+`.  
Note that `+` is a [regular expressions][1] metacharacter so you need to escape it when you want to [split][2] the string of the polynomial into terms.

After splitting into terms, you want to extract the coefficient and the exponent from each term.  
The coefficient is the number before the `x` and the exponent is the number after `x^`. Of-course a term may not contain `x` and may not contain `^` so you need to handle those cases as well.  
In the below code, I use method [indexOf][3] to locate the coefficient and the exponent and then I use method [substring][4] to extract both of them.

I am unfamiliar with class `Polynomial` so I assume it is a class that you wrote, however I couldn&#39;t find the code for that class in your question so I wrote my own. In the below code, `Polynomial` is a singly-linked list where each node in the list is an instance of class `Term` (which is another class I wrote) and a `Term` contains both a coefficient and an exponent.

In the below code, I read a line from the text file, split it into terms, extract the coefficient and exponent from each term, create a `Term` instance and add it to the `Polynomial` instance.  
The `print` statements in the below code are only for debugging purposes.
```java
import java.io.BufferedReader;
import java.io.File;
import java.io.FileNotFoundException;
import java.io.FileReader;
import java.io.IOException;
import java.nio.file.Files;
import java.nio.file.Paths;
import java.util.Arrays;

public class Proj2 {
    public static void poly() {
        try (BufferedReader br = Files.newBufferedReader(Paths.get(&quot;polynomials.txt&quot;))) {
            String line = br.readLine();
            while (line != null) {
